{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"50c520c8-2b40-4a7c-a6ce-e6c3cdd21124","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events API** in your `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n- Each handler receives the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call native APIs directly.\n- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4cc7c959-8ac1-4b5c-a26e-d81a6ead050a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI, not a codebase-specific task.","outputTokens":354,"requestId":"103E:92DE6:15A6B59:183E1DA:69FD33F0"},"id":"c6ef4d8a-731b-472b-8593-8cab5a5538d7","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:54:34.180Z","parentId":"a7a73c59-50b8-474d-a4a6-de41fed82dd5"}
